                    "company": "Maastricht University",
                    "description": "Prof. Mody teaches the history of science, technology, and innovation.  His own research focuses on the history of very recent physical and engineering sciences (~1970 to the present), with particular emphasis on the creation of new communities and institutions of research in the late Cold War and the post-Cold War periods.  His book, Instrumental Community: Probe Microscopy and the Path to Nanotechnology (2011, MIT Press) explores the co-evolution of an experimental technology (the scanning tunneling microscope and atomic force microscope and their variants) and the community of researchers who built, bought, used, sold, theorized, or borrowed these instruments.  Currently, he is finishing a monograph, entitled The Long Arm of Moore's Law, on the ways that the semiconductor industry has reshaped US science and science policy since the early '70s.  He is just beginning a new, collaborative project on the co-production of science, technology, and the cultural and economic sea changes in North American and European societies in the late '60s and '70s.",
                    "title": "Chair in History of Science, Technology, and Innovation",
                    "employment_type": null
                }
